{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"53b15a38-243b-491b-8bb9-0c8cc4fe0343","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer packages needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → versions are mismatched → you need `update`, not `repair`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try a clean restore:\n\n```bash\ndotnet clean && dotnet restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"872231b5-f675-4f86-9303-57dc4f20de56","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":248,"requestId":"111E:3A9E72:BAE3B7:DB1AC6:69FE8542"},"id":"31848a77-ceab-4286-9f9c-5f710c376a83","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:52:26.193Z","parentId":"9fe2d2d2-0fc3-4f36-b650-8ed946ddc273"}
